WEBVTT

00:02.748 --> 00:10.421
Today's interview is with James Harvey Kattis, 
retired associate professor of mechanical

00:02.748 --> 00:10.421
engineering at Texas A&M University. Today's 
date is August 2, 1982. Let's begin, Professor

00:13.986 --> 00:21.919
Kattis, by you telling us something about your 
early years. Where were you born? Oh, I was born in

00:23.863 --> 00:26.868
the town of Winona, Mississippi. Where is that? 
That's in the north central part of Mississippi,

00:28.955 --> 00:36.642
about 100 miles north of Jackson, right in the 
middle of the state. What year were you born? In

00:40.026 --> 00:41.327
1911.

00:43.509 --> 00:46.692
What was your father's occupation? My father's 
occupation, he was a farmer, he was a railroad

00:46.712 --> 00:58.303
woman, he was a night watchman and he spent his last 
years running a little store. He had a little

01:07.039 --> 01:26.923
one-horse store and about three miles out from 
town he conceived that that was a good place for a

01:07.039 --> 01:26.923
store and he opened up a store there and ran it for 
about 27 years till he was some 83 years old and had

01:07.039 --> 01:26.923
to give it up. What was the population of Winona 
back in the 20s when you were a child? About 3,000.

01:33.087 --> 01:36.831
What about your mother? Did she work or was she a 
housewife? She was a housewife. Did you graduate

01:41.978 --> 01:44.481
from high school in Winona? Yes. How did you get 
from Winona to Texas A&M? Oh, I hitchhiked. What

01:51.509 --> 01:53.772
caused you to decide to come to Texas A&M? I'd heard 
about it, and then I had the option of going to

01:55.895 --> 02:06.871
Mississippi State, which is in Starksville, 
which is in Mississippi A&M. And student labor was

02:08.152 --> 02:11.958
for 15 cents an hour there. Over here, it was 25 
cents an hour.

02:19.909 --> 02:24.636
Why did you decide to study engineering?

02:26.287 --> 02:41.278
I had always been mechanically inclined and I had 
worked one summer in an ice plant in my hometown and

02:26.287 --> 02:41.278
I liked to see machinery run and like to take over 
things and make them run. What year did you

02:43.663 --> 02:46.790
graduate from high school? 1928. And you came then 
to A&M and graduated with a bachelor's degree in

02:47.667 --> 02:53.415
1932. That's correct. You stayed here four years. 
Right. You were in the Corps at the time. Right.

02:59.062 --> 03:00.224
Which was mandatory. Right. What were your 
impressions of being in the Corps at this? Oh, it

03:06.152 --> 03:08.996
was quite a normal thing. I took a pride in it, got a 
reserve commission out of it, and... I recommend

03:17.418 --> 03:19.580
it to anybody right now.

03:22.943 --> 03:32.612
What were some of the experiences that you had here 
at Texas A&M as a student down at graduate level?

03:32.632 --> 03:34.714
What were some of the highlights of your time? One 
of the highlights of my time here was that I

03:34.734 --> 03:44.083
remember the work I did on the side, much more 
really than I do the course work. The course work, I

03:49.378 --> 03:56.148
was able to take in stride and not get behind on it. 
And that 25 cents an hour helped keep my head and

03:56.168 --> 04:01.655
soul intact. What was something you had to do? Oh, I 
had to put in the foundry. I had to put in the, what do

04:08.064 --> 04:12.670
you call it, the steam lab over there. The 
mechanical engineering shop building was new in

04:13.088 --> 04:18.714
those days. After we got through building on 
those, the original installation and everything

04:18.734 --> 04:25.921
was in operation. Then I got to doing cabin 
network. Of course, a little while earlier, I'd

04:28.744 --> 04:35.131
done a little plumbing work, too.

04:35.151 --> 04:39.616
While you were here working on your master's 
degree, you had a great impression of the city.

04:39.636 --> 04:41.037
What were your impressions of the area? Well, you 
took it in stride, but when I graduated, the only

04:42.080 --> 05:00.392
way in 1932, the only way you wanted to get a job was 
to have a pull like your father was on the board of

04:42.080 --> 05:00.392
directors of some company or something of the 
sort. You didn't get just ordinary jobs. I was one

05:04.960 --> 05:13.230
that was selected by the General Electric Company 
for a job, but they said, we just put you on hold. We

05:14.231 --> 05:16.194
can't put you to work right now. And there they 
meant it. Instead of putting some to work, they let

05:22.161 --> 05:26.987
off some safety one Young engineers that had been 
with them one or two years up in Schenectady, where

05:27.153 --> 05:34.602
I would have worked. Later they did offer me a job, 
but I was otherwise employed. When you were a

05:41.289 --> 05:47.136
senior at A&M in 1932, were there any recruiters 
who came on campus? No. Not like later times? No. No

05:51.842 --> 05:53.644
recruiters. You'd go out and hunt a job. Did many of 
the people in your class have difficulty finding

05:57.157 --> 06:03.864
jobs as engineers? All of them did. The only way a 
fella could get a job then was to have a pull, to have

06:04.404 --> 06:15.676
somebody who was in a supervisory capacity and 
could put you in. What did most of the students do

06:15.696 --> 06:20.421
when they couldn't find jobs as engineers? I had 
one student who, in the name of Porter, that went

06:20.441 --> 06:26.607
back to His hometown of Belkin started running the 
billing station. He was working in the billing

06:33.287 --> 06:35.049
station. Later on, he became the owner of the 
billing station or the contract mobile station.

06:42.938 --> 06:46.703
Later on, he was mayor of the town and a good many 
other things. I've lost track of him, but I had

06:46.723 --> 06:51.308
another one by the name of Charlie Young. He went 
back and did the same old sort of thing in the town of

06:51.329 --> 06:56.695
Kyle and ended up with As a contractor at a hardware 
store, they did what they had to. They did what they

07:05.955 --> 07:07.258
should do. What did you decide to do after your 
graduation? Oh, that summer I went up and I was

07:11.726 --> 07:17.957
going to get... General Electric put me to work at 
some capacity, so long as I keep body and soul

07:18.393 --> 07:28.969
intact, I want to go to work and get some 
experience. But

07:28.989 --> 07:36.621
when I got up to Schenectady, I hitchhiked up 
there. I found that they just laid off those 71

07:37.681 --> 07:44.810
young engineers that had been there just ahead of 
us. Any number of those would have stayed under the

07:44.830 --> 07:49.817
same conditions that I would have gone to work for 
them. So, no job then. But I lucked into a job as an

07:53.182 --> 08:04.116
athletic director, bus driver on General Flunky 
and a girl's camp in Peterborough, New Hampshire.

08:04.136 --> 08:07.080
And I spent that summer in Peterborough, New 
Hampshire. Well, yes. I stayed

08:09.109 --> 08:18.021
there eight weeks. And I made enough money to buy me 
a motorcycle. And I took a shortcut on up to Quebec

08:25.452 --> 08:38.130
and St. Anne de BeauprÃ© and on up the river there and 
came back down through Vermont. back down to New

08:38.515 --> 08:43.520
York, Washington, going back home. And I got a 
temporary job in my hometown, and after so long a

08:43.540 --> 08:56.052
time, I got an offer from Professor Crawford, who 
was head of mechanical engineering, to come back

08:43.540 --> 08:56.052
over. I thought he'd get me into the graduate 
assistant. Well, I came over considerably early.

09:04.975 --> 09:09.189
And I went back to my job of doing cabinet work. What 
did you start as a director, Susan? In the fall of

09:14.165 --> 09:17.415
1933.

09:18.813 --> 09:36.747
Professor Crawford

09:18.813 --> 09:36.747
apparently helped a lot of students get

09:18.813 --> 09:36.747
situated in graduate system type jobs and so 
forth. Is that true? That is certainly true. I've

09:37.529 --> 09:38.130
talked with him a number. He said he did tremendous 
labor by helping them get situated. Then you

09:39.957 --> 09:46.426
finished up your master's science degree in the 
summer of 1934. It took you one year to teach. It

09:49.450 --> 09:51.513
took me 12 months. You were teaching half-time 
while you were doing that. What were you teaching

09:55.839 --> 09:56.920
in graduate school? I taught what we called 
engineering problems. It was then a required

10:00.425 --> 10:04.190
course for freshmen. For freshmen, yes. What were 
some of your experiences as a graduate

10:07.058 --> 10:19.719
teaching assistant

10:07.058 --> 10:19.719
in the 1930s? Oh, it was a pleasant, challenging 
work. It was methodical. It was teaching and

10:27.171 --> 10:30.957
reading the paper. It was the only part of it that 
wasn't a real pleasure. I've always been able to

10:34.345 --> 10:37.328
work and made a great paper. There's more than just 
a few. What was the subject of your master's

10:40.913 --> 10:44.557
thesis? The subject of my master's thesis was kill 
drying certain Texas hardwood for cabinet

10:44.577 --> 10:53.267
use. Why must you search

10:53.287 --> 10:56.911
it? I worked on it about one season. actually

11:00.451 --> 11:19.135
we had a kill and we were getting this post oak 
lumber and walnut and some more local lumbers and

11:00.451 --> 11:19.135
we had to kill dry that and the question was how to 
kill dry it. And we experimentally took the thing

11:19.739 --> 11:41.091
on as not only a project to kill dry the wood, but to 
control the conditions within the kiln so that you

11:19.739 --> 11:41.091
had an increasing temperature and an increasing 
relative humidity in the kiln. And if you didn't

11:41.111 --> 11:46.759
control it just right, this post-oak will turn 
blue. turned into a material that is so hard that

11:47.228 --> 12:00.404
you're running, you're running saw just to cut a 
piece of board in

11:47.228 --> 12:00.404
two. What did you do after you completed your 
master's science degree? I went to work with the

12:05.671 --> 12:10.917
Gulf Oil, Gulf Oil Refinery in Fort Hoffa.

12:11.438 --> 12:12.780
That was in 1944, right. How did you happen to find a 
job somewhere in the family? Well, with a master's

12:15.477 --> 12:21.505
degree and the jobs, we were getting to open up a 
little bit. And I had some sum of $100 a month while

12:21.525 --> 12:26.552
they employed us. So you weren't there for seven 
years? No. I worked there about a year and a half.

12:31.338 --> 12:33.220
Where was this? Port Arthur. Port Arthur. What 
happened after that? In contrast with that, see,

12:39.428 --> 12:44.455
I'd kept up my commission in the reserves. And I was 
just on the verge of promotion to first

12:44.755 --> 12:51.583
lieutenant. The first lieutenant got $173 and 
some cents with pay and allowances. And that

12:59.774 --> 13:07.864
contrasted considerably with my $100 salary, 
which they were holding. And they were going to

13:07.884 --> 13:11.488
give raises, but they never had to get around to it. 
Yeah, that was 1935. I

13:17.671 --> 13:29.863
went on active duty with the Army in command of a 
Civilian Conservation Corps camp. Well, I was

13:30.304 --> 13:40.013
first over near Rusk, and then I was over in Milam. 
Milam is where I commanded you. The CCC,

13:42.232 --> 14:00.573
it happened, was a real fortunate thing for the 
country, outside of two or three reasons. One was

14:00.593 --> 14:08.121
it took a bunch of young men who were unemployed 
otherwise, I'm not talking about the reserve

14:08.978 --> 14:12.781
officers and all that commanded them, but it 
applied to them too. But the rank and file of the

14:13.502 --> 14:37.483
trainees in the CCC camp were young men who went in 
there and they learned how to drive trucks, they

14:13.502 --> 14:37.483
learned how to drive bulldozers, they learned how 
to make roads, build fences, do all sorts of

14:13.502 --> 14:37.483
things, and they learned how to cook, make, be an 
incumbent clerk, and each one of those things, in

14:38.864 --> 14:54.960
effect, made a cadre of people who were available 
for the United States Army, not by direct

14:38.864 --> 14:54.960
transfer, but by individual transfer. When World 
War II came along, along about that same time, our

14:55.600 --> 15:04.669
standing army was 125,000.

15:06.455 --> 15:12.444
now a million and a quarter

15:06.455 --> 15:12.444
or more. Had it not been for a reserve

15:13.024 --> 15:30.910
cadre of people out of the CCC camp, which was 
nearly triple the size of the standing army, we

15:13.024 --> 15:30.910
couldn't have mobilized the force if we did it 
nearly so quickly. Those

15:31.835 --> 15:47.761
camps

15:31.835 --> 15:47.761
all had a definite mission. Some of them were 
forest camps, reforestation. They would go in and

15:50.626 --> 15:58.939
make roads through the forest to serve for 
transportation and also for fire lanes. and they

15:59.594 --> 16:26.648
built watchtowers for lookout towers for fires 
and did some actual reforestation and they then

15:59.594 --> 16:26.648
they had camps that uh some of them uh well you take 
up here to fort parker and uh just this side of my ham

16:27.050 --> 16:29.995
They went in there and built a state park. They 
built a dam on the Navasota River, and there's a big

16:31.117 --> 16:42.836
lake in there now, a recreation facility, and all 
the camp, places you can go and camp. It's a

16:43.637 --> 16:47.924
recreation facility, a good big one. There are 
others that were soil conservation camps. They

16:51.856 --> 17:08.556
went in and actually did the terracing, did the 
survey work, the terracing and whatnot to make

16:51.856 --> 17:08.556
maximum use of rainfall and control soil erosion.

17:10.979 --> 17:13.002
And a good many others. They were all in there for a 
definite purpose, and they were...

17:21.877 --> 17:24.220
The public didn't resent those at all. And there 
was enough discipline. Those boys went out and

17:27.845 --> 17:30.088
actually worked. In those days, when a man worked, 
he worked.

17:37.759 --> 17:43.046
We hear impressions of Franklin Roosevelt. Much 
better then than now.

17:52.471 --> 18:03.246
I found later that some of the big improvements 
that he made in the banking facilities, you know,

17:52.471 --> 18:03.246
banks all went broke. Not all of them, but a great 
number of banks went broke. They closed the doors

18:08.153 --> 18:12.859
and all back in the Great Depression. A great many 
of those big improvements were actually the

18:13.430 --> 18:20.259
fruits of Herbert Hoover. President Hoover had a 
great many of those things going, but when

18:20.279 --> 18:38.965
Franklin Roosevelt became president, the 
furthest thing in the action there was to give

18:20.279 --> 18:38.965
credit to the prior administration, which had 
been Republican. And the other thing is that under

18:40.396 --> 18:59.199
the Roosevelt administration, socialism began 
in this country as never before, and it's still

18:40.396 --> 18:59.199
going.

18:59.219 --> 19:07.770
One

18:59.219 --> 19:07.770
is this business of make work by the government. 
Fortunately, in those days, the country was in a

19:09.927 --> 19:24.440
mood where when you made some work by the people who 
worked, and the WPA worked, it was far less

19:09.927 --> 19:24.440
efficient than the CCC. But nonetheless, they did 
some good jobs. But it came into the fact that it got

19:28.284 --> 19:37.572
out of the way, the fact that a person

19:38.767 --> 19:53.669
Each man was an individual, each circumstance was 
an individual circumstance, and the government

19:38.767 --> 19:53.669
was obliged to go in and take care of everybody.

19:53.689 --> 20:04.705
It has gradually progressed until people are not 
permitted to be poor, if you know what I mean. I

20:04.725 --> 20:08.250
believe the good book says the poor shall inherit 
the earth, They certainly have, but in contrast,

20:09.378 --> 20:27.205
they're why

20:09.378 --> 20:27.205
it's got to the point now that if they get enough 
handouts, they won't work.

20:27.225 --> 20:34.356
You're not about to hire a fellow on a menial job 
who's on this welfare kick. You might lose it. In

