talk freely about what goes on over there, and 
before, I had the experience, and she couldn't,

31:35.127 --> 31:45.722
because you can't conceive, really. You see a lot 
of stuff on the TV, you know, but you can't really

31:46.543 --> 32:02.485
conceive the conditions and the people and how 
they exist and the difference between the

31:46.543 --> 32:02.485
ordinary people and the educated people and the 
government, the politicians. You've got three

32:03.241 --> 32:05.424
different levels. Common, poor people. Then 
you've got the ordinary people that are educated,

32:07.947 --> 32:17.879
middle-class people, and some of them are 
high-class, too. And then you've got the

32:17.899 --> 32:31.695
government

32:17.899 --> 32:31.695
bureaucrats or the autocrats, in this case might 
be the politicians.

32:34.274 --> 32:41.382
So when you see something on the news about 
Bangladesh, do you know more about it than comes to

32:34.274 --> 32:41.382
the other person around your house? Well, some 
truth. Do you have any problem with the language?

32:49.391 --> 32:50.512
We're talking English. I learned a little of the 
language. I learned a little of the language when I

32:53.756 --> 32:58.081
was over there in World War II. What? No, you've got 
many languages over there. Bengali

33:04.683 --> 33:19.944
is the language of some hundred million people in 
that general area.

33:19.964 --> 33:29.998
People who speak Bengali, they don't have too much 
overlap between that and people who speak Hindi,

33:19.964 --> 33:29.998
or the people who speak Urdu, or the people who... 
When I was there in World War II, the money was in the

33:30.232 --> 33:35.440
British India. British India, which didn't 
include all of the areas, it included the bulk of

33:37.063 --> 33:44.355
them. The money they had was in groupie notes. A 
little note, one rupee note was small. Five rupees

33:51.737 --> 33:54.160
was a little bigger. Ten rupees was bigger. Twenty 
rupees was still bigger. A hundred rupees would be

33:58.085 --> 34:03.070
like bed sheets.

34:05.914 --> 34:14.123
Everything bigger than a one rupee note had eight 
written languages on it. There's eight written

34:14.143 --> 34:15.645
languages. Now here's some 400 dilators 
scattered all

34:17.026 --> 34:27.401
over. What did she exactly do? I taught classes, 
and I consulted with the principal, who was the

34:30.593 --> 34:46.092
same as the president of the institution, and with 
the head of the mechanical engineering

34:30.593 --> 34:46.092
department. We helped provide for them some 
particular pieces of equipment, some

34:46.112 --> 34:52.319
literature. I wrote one book while I was there, and 
one more. on engineering problems. And the idea

35:02.246 --> 35:21.085
was to get an elementary book in there that would 
bring together to a more or less common foundation

35:02.246 --> 35:21.085
a diversity of backgrounds that these students 
had who got there. Some of them were ready to go

35:21.265 --> 35:29.794
ahead with a little bit higher work, and some of 
them were not. The bulk of them needed to, the

35:30.550 --> 35:38.658
education, the higher education, they were in 
English, in engineering, and still is. And

35:40.960 --> 35:48.747
they couldn't speak and handle the language well 
enough to get on with it. They needed some

35:48.767 --> 35:56.895
elementary, fundamental problems where you come 
down to what's given, what's required, and

35:57.179 --> 36:03.148
present the solution in an orderly, step-by-step 
fashion. A&M

36:03.168 --> 36:15.587
was involved in that because A&M was one of the land 
grant institutions.

36:16.088 --> 36:21.837
We were recognized to have a substantial 
engineering and agricultural capability and

36:22.778 --> 36:41.766
it's in those two prime areas that they were 
helping these countries so-called third world

36:22.778 --> 36:41.766
countries

36:22.778 --> 36:41.766
and you came back

36:45.020 --> 37:05.442
We have one

36:45.020 --> 37:05.442
son.

37:05.759 --> 37:13.008
And the year we went over there, he was a freshman at 
A&M, and he stayed here and went through his

37:05.759 --> 37:13.008
freshman year. Then he had ambition to go over 
there too, so he went over there and attended

37:13.569 --> 37:19.336
college. He didn't credit for it, but he attended 
college for the better part of a year and took

37:19.356 --> 37:30.990
courses and went to the University of Dhaka. And 
then he came back here and went on to graduate

37:32.978 --> 37:39.708
at the A&M University. Okay, you came back in 58. 
You were associate professor of mechanical

37:41.911 --> 37:47.320
engineering when you came back. And you held that 
position until you retired in 1979. What type of

37:49.303 --> 37:53.569
research did you do in 58, 57, and 68? I did not do 
direct research. I was always loaded with guilt on

38:00.446 --> 38:06.191
teaching. And in addition to teaching here, the 
last nine months, I mean the last

38:06.212 --> 38:23.269
nine semesters that I've taught extension 
courses down at Kelly Air Force Base in San

38:06.212 --> 38:23.269
Antonio. You taught engineering problems or what 
else? Oh, I taught 28 different courses, I think.

38:34.498 --> 38:38.162
Did you teach all the undergraduates or graduates 
as well? I taught some graduate work. What were

38:42.007 --> 38:50.657
some of the changes that occurred at A&M when you 
came back from 58 into retirement in 76?

38:54.113 --> 39:02.986
Well, one of them was moving over to the new 
building from old Fermion Hall. You remember

39:05.109 --> 39:07.753
Fermion? You know where the industrial, the 
engineering technology offices are there now?

39:17.126 --> 39:18.248
You mean shops? Well, see, we had, that was the 
Fermier Building. Professor Fermier was one time

39:22.577 --> 39:30.508
the head, way back there, the head of the 
Mechanical Engineering Department. And after

39:30.808 --> 39:40.702
his death, that building was completed and named 
it for himself. F-E-R-M-I-E-R. Sometime after

39:42.224 --> 39:46.170
that, they completed the shop building. He was 
actually a great man and a great builder, and they

39:46.290 --> 40:02.596
put up the buildings in his time, and there was a lot 
of progress in mechanical engineering in that

39:46.290 --> 40:02.596
time, and they named the building for him. The shop 
building has never been named for

40:02.616 --> 40:09.227
anybody. I'm

40:10.388 --> 40:21.043
seeing changes in two directions. One is good and 
one is bad.

40:28.713 --> 40:35.603
The bad feature is that students

40:41.219 --> 40:47.987
not as serious as they

40:41.219 --> 40:47.987
used to be. Too many of them are pouring with a 
silver spoon in their mouth, and the old work ethic

40:48.007 --> 41:04.105
is not properly ingrained into them now that they 
get to college, and they're just a bunch of kids

40:48.007 --> 41:04.105
still in school. And the best students we ever had 
were those right after World War II that had been in

41:05.857 --> 41:13.485
the service. They called them GIs. And the GI 
student came back, and he had his hard knocks, and

41:16.608 --> 41:32.725
he had seen the difference between the officer 
rank and the enlisted rank, the difference in pay,

41:16.608 --> 41:32.725
and a lot of them had all gone out and got jobs in 
industry, and they saw the difference between

41:16.608 --> 41:32.725
them. and the bosses and the people and the 
workers. And they were downright, and they also

41:40.047 --> 41:45.094
were a few years older than the others. And the 
seriousness they had made them be the best

41:46.496 --> 41:51.743
students that we ever had. I've heard several of 
the things that I'm taught to say to that class of 46

41:51.963 --> 41:57.531
and 47 were, It was the best I'd ever seen. 46, 47, it 
extended right on up

42:01.056 --> 42:07.285
to... It sort of phased out, but that extended on up 
to about, oh, in the early 50s. I'd say

42:15.335 --> 42:24.227
in the matter of 53, we still were getting a lot of 
so-called GIs. We were getting them then that had

42:25.507 --> 42:35.059
been out working more, and some of them stayed in 
the Army

42:25.507 --> 42:35.059
a little bit longer. We had good students then, and 
they were not writer's students,

42:35.079 --> 42:47.734
but they were more

42:35.079 --> 42:47.734
diligent. Kind of like football, you know, you 
take an ordinary player who's got his heart set to

42:47.754 --> 42:54.923
do a job, You come a whole lot nearer to getting it 
done than some fellow that's got all sorts of

42:55.544 --> 43:07.639
ability and only half-hearted and 
half-professional.

43:07.659 --> 43:13.006
What about the changes that occur as a result of the 
Corps being made voluntary? You see, that effect

43:13.026 --> 43:19.374
on the university as well. That change, 
unfortunately or unfortunately as it may be,

43:26.307 --> 43:30.772
There's good and there's bad in that. I was part of 
the old army gang where everybody was required to

43:31.052 --> 43:47.151
be in there and I've seen, I've taught on through 
the time when only a quarter of the people were in

43:31.052 --> 43:47.151
the Corps. And the Corps is not for everybody and 
everybody's not for the Corps. If you take a fellow

43:53.577 --> 44:04.130
who has a disdain for the military, why, the Corps 
shouldn't have to put up with you. On the other

44:04.150 --> 44:19.568
hand, the training and discipline they get in the 
Corps is certainly a thing that has given Texas A&M

44:04.150 --> 44:19.568
graduates a reputation for personnel 
management, being able to get along with people

44:21.286 --> 44:26.552
and do things. But A&M has given a real reputation 
that the people from liberal arts schools or the

44:28.595 --> 44:43.713
schools that did not have military never got.

44:44.013 --> 44:51.242
Now, that period of change happened to coincide 
with the period of the 60s. in which you had all the

44:51.492 --> 45:07.273
Vietnam draft dodges, and all of the burning of the 
ROTCs in not A&M, thank goodness, but in Facebook,

44:51.492 --> 45:07.273
Columbia, you name it. A lot of those places where 
they went in and literally set fire to the ROTC

45:07.293 --> 45:17.787
buildings and did other damage. had all their 
parades. They did their thing out at Berkeley.

45:27.807 --> 45:45.023
And to the extent that that exists, why, I'd say the 
non-military is a bane on the, it's a bane on

45:27.807 --> 45:45.023
democracy.

